The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

NATION BRIEFS

 Pune, June 29 (PTI): Fines of over Rs 251.26 crore the highest ordered by an Indian court have been slapped on stamp-paper scam mastermind Abdul Karim Telgi.

 The total fines imposed by a special court, which yesterday sentenced Telgi to 13 years rigorous imprisonment in one of the main cases, is Rs 251,26,05,000.

 Kottayam (PTI): An AIDS rehabilitation centre has offered to take care of the education of five HIV-positive children who are facing a boycott at a Pampady school. If the state permits, we will appoint a teacher and provide tuition. Later, they can sit for school examinations, an official of the centre said.

 New Delhi (PTI): CBSE students now have the option of mentioning their mothers name and orphans can give their guardians name while registering for the board exams. They can also mention either their mothers or fathers name or both for records like certificates.

 Chennai (PTI): An Air India flight with 178 passengers made an emergency landing here after developing problems in the hydraulic system. Airport officials said the flight from Mumbai developed problems when it was about to land in Bangkok but was not permitted to land there. The flight was then diverted to Chennai.

 Chandigarh (PTI): Punjab and Haryana High Court has granted Dera Sacha Sauda chief Gurmeet Ram Rahim Singh interim bail till August 6 in a case on hurting Sikh sentiments.

 New Delhi (PTI): One IIT, one IIM and an Indian Institute of Information Technology will be set up in Bihar during the 11th plan period. Every district in the state will have a UGC-aided college.

 Mumbai (PTI): One person was killed in an altercation with two fellow commuters over standing at the door of a train compartment. The two passengers have been arrested.




